Heterogeneous Slopes Experiments

What is this?

This is a simple example of working with ordered categorical predictors in a linear regression. The idea is to impose monotonicity in the relationship between an ordered discrete predictor and an outcome of interest without specifying a particular functional form for the relationship. We start with a very simple example and then augment it to resemble the structural model from our paper, by incorporating data on the distribution of land ownership in Colombian municipalities. In each case weâll use a cross-section dataset, although in the real example from the paper itâs a panel. It should still be possible to identify the effects.

Simple Regression Example

In this model, the effect of \(X\) is mediated by a discrete, ordered predictor $H_i {1, 1, â¦, J}. Later on, these will correspond to âland binsâ so the zero means landless. But for now theyâre just ordered predictors, e.g.Â levels of education. The unrestricted model is
\[ Y_i = \alpha + \beta_{j[H_i]}X_i + \epsilon_i \] This notation allows a different slope for every possible value of \(H\). This is equivalent to interacting \(X_i\) with a full set of dummy variables for the levels of \(H_i\). Now suppose that we wanted to restrict the way that \(H_i\) mediates the relationship between \(X_i\) and \(Y_i\) to ensure that higher levels of \(H_i\) correspond to lower values of \(\beta_{j[H_i]}\). A simple way to achieve this is as follows: \[ Y_i = \alpha + \beta \left(1 - \sum_{j=0}^{H_i-1} \delta_j \right) X_i + \epsilon_i \] where \(0 \leq \delta_j \leq 1\), \(\delta_0 = 0\) and \(\sum_{j=1}^{J} \delta_j = 1\). Writing this out in full: \[ \begin{align} H_i = 1 &\implies \beta_j = \beta \\ H_i = 2 &\implies \beta_j = \beta_0(1 - \delta_1)\\ H_i = 3 &\implies \beta_j = \beta_0(1 - \delta_1 - \delta_2)\\ H_i = h &\implies \beta_j = \beta_0(1 - \delta_1 - \delta_2 - ... - \delta_{h-1})\\ \end{align} \] Hereâs how to think about this model: \(\delta_1\) is the first decrement: the amount that the slope coefficient falls when moving from \(H_i = 1\) to \(H_i = 2\). More generally, \(\delta_j\) is the \(j\)th increment: the amount that the slope coefficient falls when moving from \(H_i = j\) to \(H_i = (j + 1)\). The final decrement \(\delta_J\) is never actually used to compute a coefficient. Its role is merely to ensure that the full set of \(\delta_j\) adds up to one. Notice that this model ensures the coefficients \(\beta_{j[H_i]}\) are monotonically non-increasing. To obtain a model where they are non-decreasing, simply replace \((1 - \sum)\) with \(\sum\). Notice further that in this model \(\beta\) is the effect of \(X_i\) when \(H_i = 1\).

Now weâll simulate some data from this model. To obtain the \(\delta_j\) coefficients, weâll discretize a continuous function:

J <- 10
decrements <- diff(1 / (1:J)) * -1
delta <- c(0, decrements, 1 - sum(decrements)) 
plot(0:J, 1 - cumsum(delta))

Note that \(\delta_J\) isnât actually used to define any effects, although it will be estimated by the model. Its only role is to satisfy the adding up constraint. Similarly \(\delta_0\) is neither used nor estimated: itâs just a book-keeping device that ensures \(\beta\) equals the marginal effect for people with \(H_i = 1\).

set.seed(1234)
N <- 500
X <- rnorm(N, 10) 
sigma <- 1
epsilon <- rnorm(N, sd = sigma)
alpha <- (-2)
beta <- 2
beta_j <- beta * (1 - cumsum(delta)[-(J + 1)])
H <- sample(1:J, N, replace = TRUE)
Y <- alpha + beta_j[H] * X + epsilon

plot(X, Y)

true_params <- c('alpha' = alpha,
                 'beta' = beta,
                 'delta' = delta[-1],
                 'sigma' = sigma)
library(cmdstanr)

model1 <- cmdstan_model('ordered-categorical-predictor-regression.stan')
model1$print()
data {
  int J;
  int N;
  array[N] int<lower=1> H;
  vector[N] X;
  vector[N] Y;
}

parameters {
  real alpha;
  real beta;
  real<lower=0> sigma;
  simplex[J] delta;
}

model {
  vector[N] mu;
  vector[J + 1] delta_j;
  delta_j = append_row(0.0, delta); // simplifies book-keeping below
  
  // Construct vector of parameters for Dirichlet prior
  vector[J] a;
  for(j in 1:J) {
    a[j] = 2.0; // change as desired: (exchangeable Dirichlet distribution)
  }
  delta ~ dirichlet(a);
  
  sigma ~ exponential(1);
  beta ~ normal(0, 2);
  alpha ~ normal(0, 2);
  
  for(i in 1:N) {
    mu[i] = alpha + beta * (1 - sum(delta_j[1:H[i]])) * X[i]; 
  }
  Y ~ normal(mu, sigma);
  
}
dat <- list(J = J, N = N, H = H, X = X, Y = Y)

fit1 <- model1$sample(
  data = dat,
  seed = 5678,
  chains = 4,
  parallel_chains = 4,
  refresh = 500,
)

Example with Land Distribution Data

Now weâll try a more complicated example that will play a role in our structural model. Imagine that we aggregated the model from the previous section within geographical units. In each city we observe the share of people with each value of \(H\). We also observe the average \(X\) and the average \(Y\). Then the city-specific slope coefficient will be the average of the \(\beta_j\) weighted by the share of people with \(H = j\) in that city. If \(\omega_h\) is the share of people with \(H = h\) then the overall effect in a city city equals \[ \begin{align*} \beta_{\text{overall}} &= \sum_{h=1}^J \omega_h \beta_h = \left[\sum_{h=1}^J \omega_h\beta \left(1 - \sum_{j=0}^{h-1} \delta_j \right) \right]\\ &= \beta \left[ \sum_{h=1}^J \left(\omega_h - \omega_h\sum_{j=0}^{h-1} \delta_j \right)\right]\\ &= \beta \left[ \left(\sum_{h=1}^J \omega_h \right) - \sum_{h=1}^J \omega_h\sum_{j=0}^{h-1} \delta_j\right]\\ &= \beta \left(1 - \sum_{j=0}^{J-1} \delta_j \sum_{h=j+1}^J \omega_h\right)\\ &= \beta \left(1 - \sum_{j=0}^{J-1} \delta_j S_{j+1}\right)\\ &= \beta \left(1 - \sum_{j=1}^{J} \delta_{j-1} S_{j}\right)\\ \end{align*} \] where we define \(S_j \equiv \sum_{k=j}^J \omega_k = 1 - \sum_{k=1}^{j-1} \omega_k\).

library(forcedMigration)
library(tidyverse)

has_land <- land_distributions |> 
  map_lgl(\(x) any(!is.na(x$frac_families)))

get_S <- function(land_dist) {
  omega <- land_dist$frac_families
  J <- length(omega)
  c(1, (1 - cumsum(omega))[-J])
}

S <- land_distributions[has_land] |> 
  map(get_S) |> 
  do.call(rbind, args = _)

colnames(S) <- rownames(land_distributions[[1]])

J <- ncol(S)
decrements <- diff(1 / (1:J)) * -1
delta <- c(0, decrements, 1 - sum(decrements))
plot(0:J, 1 - cumsum(delta))

delta_lag <- matrix(delta[-(J + 1)], J, 1)


set.seed(1234)
N <- nrow(S)
X <- rnorm(N, 10) 
sigma <- 1
epsilon <- rnorm(N, sd = sigma)
alpha <- (-2)
beta <- 2

beta_heterog <- beta * (1 - drop(S %*% delta_lag))
Y <- alpha + beta_heterog * X + epsilon

plot(X, Y)

true_params <- c('alpha' = alpha,
                 'beta' = beta,
                 'delta' = delta[-1],
                 'sigma' = sigma)

dat <- list(J = J, N = N, S = S, X = X, Y = Y)

model2 <- cmdstan_model('ordered-categorical-predictor-land-distribution.stan')
model2$print()
data {
  int<lower=0> J;
  int<lower=0> N;
  matrix[N, J] S;
  vector[N] X;
  vector[N] Y;
}

transformed data {
  vector[J] ones_J;
  for(j in 1:J) {
    ones_J[j] = 1.0;
  }
}

parameters {
  real alpha;
  real beta;
  real<lower=0> sigma;
  simplex[J] delta;
}

model {
  vector[N] mu;
  vector[N] beta_heterog;
  
  vector[J + 1] delta_j;
  delta_j = append_row(0.0, delta); // simplifies book-keeping below
 
  // Construct vector of parameters for Dirichlet prior
  real a = 2.0; // change as desired: exchangeable Dirichlet distribution
  delta ~ dirichlet(a * ones_J);
  
  sigma ~ exponential(1);
  beta ~ normal(0, 2);
  alpha ~ normal(0, 2);
  
  beta_heterog = beta * (1 - (S * delta_j[1:J]));
  mu = alpha + beta_heterog .* X;
  Y ~ normal(mu, sigma);
}
fit2 <- model2$sample(
  data = dat,
  seed = 5678,
  chains = 4,
  parallel_chains = 4,
  refresh = 500
)

Adding Unit-specific Intercepts

In the paper, we need to identify heterogeneous intercepts at the same time as heterogeneous slopes, so now weâll try a panel version of the preceding experiment.

Ni <- nrow(S)
Nt <- 3
N <- Nt * Ni
id <- rep(1:Ni, each = Nt)

# Unit-specific intercepts
abar <- (-2)
tau <- 0.5
gamma <- 1.5
sigma <- 1
eta <- rnorm(Ni)

X <- rnorm(N)
Xbar <- tibble(X, id) |> 
  group_by(id) |> 
  summarize(Xbar = mean(X)) |> 
  pull(Xbar)

alpha <- abar + gamma * Xbar + tau * eta

epsilon <- rnorm(N, sd = sigma)
Y <- alpha[id] + beta_heterog[id] * X + epsilon

model3 <- cmdstan_model('ordered-categorical-predictor-panel.stan')
model3$print()
data {
  int<lower=0> J;
  int<lower=0> Ni;
  int<lower=Ni> N;
  matrix[Ni, J] S;
  vector[N] X;
  vector[Ni] Xbar;
  vector[N] Y;
  array[N] int<lower=1> id;
}

transformed data {
  vector[J] ones_J;
  for(j in 1:J) {
    ones_J[j] = 1.0;
  }
}

parameters {
  simplex[J] delta;
  real beta;
  real gamma;
  real abar;
  real<lower=0> tau;
  vector[Ni] eta;
  real<lower=0> sigma;
}

transformed parameters {
  vector[Ni] alpha = abar + tau * eta;
}

model {
  vector[N] mu;
  vector[Ni] beta_heterog;
  
  vector[J + 1] delta_j;
  delta_j = append_row(0.0, delta); // simplifies book-keeping below
 
  // Construct vector of parameters for Dirichlet prior
  real a = 2.0; // change as desired: exchangeable Dirichlet distribution
  delta ~ dirichlet(a * ones_J);
  
  beta ~ normal(0, 2);
  gamma ~ normal(0, 2);
  abar ~ normal(0, 2);
  eta ~ normal(0, 1);
  tau ~ exponential(1);
  sigma ~ exponential(1);
  
  beta_heterog = beta * (1 - (S * delta_j[1:J]));
  for(j in 1:N) {
    mu[j] = alpha[id[j]] + beta_heterog[id[j]] * X[j] + gamma * Xbar[id[j]]; 
  }
  Y ~ normal(mu, sigma);
}
true_params <- c('abar' = abar, 
                 'tau' = tau,
                 'beta' = beta,
                 'gamma' = gamma,
                 'delta' = delta[-1],
                 'sigma' = sigma)


dat <- list(J = J, Ni = Ni, id = id, N = N, S = S, Xbar = Xbar, X = X, Y = Y)

fit3 <- model3$sample(
  data = dat,
  seed = 5678,
  chains = 4,
  parallel_chains = 4,
  refresh = 500
)

Just as a sanity check, letâs estimate the same model with a âfixed-effectsâ specification:

model4 <- cmdstan_model('ordered-categorical-predictor-FE.stan')
model4$print()
data {
  int<lower=0> J;
  int<lower=0> Ni;
  int<lower=Ni> N;
  matrix[Ni, J] S;
  vector[N] X;
  vector[N] Y;
  array[N] int<lower=1> id;
}

transformed data {
  vector[J] ones_J;
  for(j in 1:J) {
    ones_J[j] = 1.0;
  }
}

parameters {
  simplex[J] delta;
  real beta;
  vector[Ni] alpha;
  real<lower=0> sigma;
}

model {
  vector[N] mu;
  vector[Ni] beta_heterog;
  
  vector[J + 1] delta_j;
  delta_j = append_row(0.0, delta); // simplifies book-keeping below
 
  // Construct vector of parameters for Dirichlet prior
  real a = 2.0; // change as desired: exchangeable Dirichlet distribution
  delta ~ dirichlet(a * ones_J);
  
  alpha ~ normal(0, 10);
  beta ~ normal(0, 2);
  sigma ~ exponential(1);
  
  beta_heterog = beta * (1 - (S * delta_j[1:J]));
  for(j in 1:N) {
    mu[j] = alpha[id[j]] + beta_heterog[id[j]] * X[j]; 
  }
  Y ~ normal(mu, sigma);
}
fit4 <- model4$sample(
  data = dat,
  seed = 5678,
  chains = 4,
  parallel_chains = 4,
  refresh = 500
)

Poisson Example

Now letâs try a model thatâs even closer to what we plan to do in the paper, this time adding heterogeneous slopes to the DGP from poisson-panel-logXplus1.qmd.

abar <- (-2)
gamma <- 1
tau <- 0.3


mu <- log(4) + rnorm(Ni) # Rate of 4 at the average
X <- rpois(N, exp(mu[id])) 

Xtilde <- tibble(X, id) |> 
  group_by(id) |> 
  summarize(Xtilde = mean(log(1 + X))) |> 
  pull(Xtilde)

alpha <- abar + gamma * Xtilde + tau * eta
lambda <- exp(alpha[id] + beta_heterog[id] * log(X + 1)) 
Y <- rpois(N, lambda)

true_params <- c('abar' = abar, 
                 'tau' = tau,
                 'beta' = beta,
                 'gamma' = gamma,
                 'delta' = delta[-1])

dat <- list(J = J, Ni = Ni, id = id, N = N, S = S, Xtilde = Xtilde, 
            logXplus1 = log(X + 1), Y = Y)


model5 <- cmdstan_model('ordered-categorical-predictor-panel-poisson.stan')
model5$print()
data {
  int<lower=0> J;
  int<lower=0> Ni;
  int<lower=Ni> N;
  matrix[Ni, J] S;
  vector[N] logXplus1;
  vector[Ni] Xtilde;
  array[N] int<lower=0> Y;
  array[N] int<lower=1> id;
  
}

transformed data {
  vector[J] ones_J;
  for(j in 1:J) {
    ones_J[j] = 1.0;
  }
}

parameters {
  simplex[J] delta;
  real beta;
  real gamma;
  real abar;
  real<lower=0> tau;
  vector[Ni] eta;
}

transformed parameters {
  vector[Ni] alpha = abar + tau * eta;
}

model {
  vector[N] log_lambda;
  vector[Ni] beta_heterog;
  
  vector[J + 1] delta_j;
  delta_j = append_row(0.0, delta); // simplifies book-keeping below
 
  // Construct vector of parameters for Dirichlet prior
  real a = 2.0; // change as desired: exchangeable Dirichlet distribution
  delta ~ dirichlet(a * ones_J);
  
  beta ~ normal(0, 2);
  gamma ~ normal(0, 2);
  abar ~ normal(0, 2);
  eta ~ normal(0, 1);
  tau ~ exponential(1);
  
  beta_heterog = beta * (1 - (S * delta_j[1:J]));
  
  for(j in 1:N) {
    log_lambda[j] = alpha[id[j]] + beta_heterog[id[j]] * logXplus1[j] + 
    gamma * Xtilde[id[j]];
  }
  
  Y ~ poisson_log(log_lambda);
}
fit5 <- model5$sample(
  data = dat,
  seed = 5678,
  chains = 4,
  parallel_chains = 4,
  refresh = 500
)
